HEADWORD: Habitat
<hw>Hab"i*tat</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧b"⟦icr⟧*t⟦acr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L., it dwells, fr. <ets>habitare</ets>. See <er>Habit</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The natural
abode, locality or region of an animal or plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Place where anything is commonly found.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This word has its <qex>habitat</qex> in Oxfordshire.</q>
<rj><qau>Earle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Habitation</ent>⟦br⟧
